  "target_response": {
    "text": "Sleep efficiency is the share of your time in bed actually spent asleep, and your 84% is one point of difference from the cutoff you read — that's noise, not a verdict. Web thresholds are population rules of thumb; they aren't measurements of you. Your own record looks steady: you slept 7.5 h last night, right on your 30-day average of 7.4 h, and night-level efficiency from a wrist device is sensor-estimated anyway, so single-point precision simply isn't there. The personal signal that would matter is a multi-week slide in efficiency alongside growing awake time, and your log doesn't show one. If falling or staying asleep starts feeling like a nightly struggle, act on that regardless of the score — otherwise this reads as an ordinary night by your own history.",
    "expected_action": "answer",
